[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] Another way to describe differential privacy is as a constraint on the algorithms used to publish aggregate information about a statistical database which limits the disclosure of private information of records in the database.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] Roughly, an algorithm is differentially private if an observer seeing its output cannot tell whether a particular individual's information was used in the computation.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] Differential privacy is often discussed in the context of identifying individuals whose information may be in a database.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] Although it does not directly refer to identification and reidentification attacks, differentially private algorithms provably resist such attacks.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] The 2006 Cynthia Dwork, Frank McSherry, Kobbi Nissim, and Adam D.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] Smith article introduced the concept of ε-differential privacy, a mathematical definition for the privacy loss associated with any data release drawn from a statistical database.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] The definition of ε-differential privacy requires that a change to one entry in a database only creates a small change in the probability distribution of the outputs of measurements, as seen by the attacker.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] The intuition for the definition of ε-differential privacy is that a person's privacy cannot be compromised by a statistical release if their data are not in the database.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] In differential privacy, each individual is given roughly the same privacy that would result from having their data removed.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] That is, the statistical functions run on the database should not be substantially affected by the removal, addition, or change of any individual in the data.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] How much any individual contributes to the result of a database query depends in part on how many people's data are involved in the query.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] If the database contains data from a single person, that person's data contributes 100%.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] If the database contains data from a hundred people, each person's data contributes just 1%.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] The key insight of differential privacy is that as the query is made on the data of fewer and fewer people, more noise needs to be added to the query result to produce the same amount of privacy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] Let ε be a positive real number and ${\mathcal {A}}$ be a randomized algorithm that takes a dataset as input (representing the actions of the trusted party holding the data).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/differential-privacy] Let ${\textrm {im}}\ {\mathcal {A}}$ denote the image of ${\mathcal {A}}$ .
