[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Local differential privacy (LDP) is an approach to mitigate the concern of data fusion and analysis techniques used to expose individuals to attacks and disclosures.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] LDP is a well-known privacy model for distributed architectures that aims to provide privacy guarantees for each user while collecting and analyzing data, protecting from privacy leaks for the client and server.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] LDP has been widely adopted to alleviate contemporary privacy concerns in the era of big data.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The randomized response survey technique proposed by Stanley L.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Warner in 1965 is frequently cited as an example of local differential privacy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Warner's innovation was the introduction of what could now be called the "untrusted curator" model, where the entity collecting the data may not be trustworthy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Before users' responses are sent to the curator, the answers are randomized in a controlled manner, guaranteeing differential privacy while still allowing valid population-wide statistical inferences.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Evfimievski, Johannes Gehrke, and Ramakrishnan Srikant gave a definition equivalent to local differential privacy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] In 2008, Kasiviswanathan et al. first used the term "local private learning" and showed it to be equivalent to randomized response.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The era of big data exhibits a high demand for machine learning services that provide privacy protection for users.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Demand for such services has pushed research into algorithmic paradigms that provably satisfy specific privacy requirements.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Anomaly detection is formally defined as the process of identifying unexpected items or events in data sets.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The rise of social networking in the current era has led to many potential concerns related to information privacy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] As more and more users rely on social networks, they are often threatened by privacy breaches, unauthorized access to personal information, and leakage of sensitive data.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] To attempt to solve this issue, the authors of "Anomaly Detection over Differential Preserved Privacy in Online Social Networks" have proposed a model using a social network utilizing restricted local differential privacy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] By using this model, it aims for improved privacy preservation through anomaly detection.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] In this paper, the authors propose a privacy preserving model that sanitizes the collection of user information from a social network utilizing restricted local differential privacy (LDP) to save synthetic copies of collected data.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] This model uses reconstructed data to classify user activity and detect abnormal network behavior.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The experimental results demonstrate that the proposed method achieves high data utility on the basis of improved privacy preservation.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Furthermore, local differential privacy sanitized data are suitable for use in subsequent analyses, such as anomaly detection.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Anomaly detection on the proposed method's reconstructed data achieves a detection accuracy similar to that on the original data.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Potential combinations of blockchain technology with local differential privacy have received research attention.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Blockchains implement distributed, secured, and shared ledgers used to record and track data within a decentralized network, and they have successfully replaced certain prior systems of economic transactions within and between organizations.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Increased usage of blockchains has raised some questions regarding privacy and security of data they store, and local differential privacy of various kinds has been proposed as a desirable property for blockchains containing sensitive data.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Local differential privacy provides context-free privacy even in the absence of a trusted data collector, though often at the expense of a significant drop in utility.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The classical definition of LDP assumes that all elements in the data domain are equally sensitive.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] However, in many applications, some symbols are more sensitive than others.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] A context-aware framework of local differential privacy can allow a privacy designer to incorporate the application's context into the privacy definition.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] For binary data domains, algorithmic research has provided a universally optimal privatization scheme and highlighted its connections to Warner's randomized response (RR) and Mangat's improved response.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] For k-ary data domains, motivated by geolocation and web search applications, researchers have considered at least two special cases of context-aware LDP: block-structured LDP and high-low LDP (the latter is also defined in ).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The research has provided communication-efficient, sample-optimal schemes and information theoretic lower bounds for both models.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Facial recognition has become widespread in recent years.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Recent smartphones, for example, utilize facial recognition to unlock the users phone as well as authorize the payment with their credit card.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Though this is convenient, it poses privacy concerns.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] It is a resource-intensive task that often involves third party users, often resulting in a gap where the user's privacy could be compromised.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Biometric information delivered to untrusted third-party servers in an uncontrolled manner can constitute a significant privacy leak as biometrics can be correlated with sensitive data such as healthcare or financial records.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] In Chamikara's academic article, he proposes a privacy-preserving technique for "controlled information release", where they disguise an original face image and prevent leakage of the biometric features while identifying a person.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] He introduces a new privacy-preserving face recognition protocol named PEEP (Privacy using Eigenface Perturbation) that utilizes local differential privacy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] PEEP applies perturbation to Eigenfaces utilizing differential privacy and stores only the perturbed data in the third-party servers to run a standard Eigenface recognition algorithm.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] As a result, the trained model will not be vulnerable to privacy attacks such as membership inference and model memorization attacks.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] This model provided by Chami kara shows the potential solution of this issue or privacy leaks.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Federated learning has the ambition to protect data privacy through distributed learning methods that keep the data in its storage.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Likewise, differential privacy (DP) attains to improve the protection of data privacy by measuring the privacy loss in the communication among the elements of federated learning.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The rapid growth of health data, the limited storage and computation resources of wireless body area sensor networks is becoming a barrier to the development of the health industry to keep up.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Aiming to solve this, the outsourcing of encrypted health data to the cloud has been an appealing strategy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] However, there may come potential downsides as do all choices.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Data aggregation will become more difficult and more vulnerable to data branches of this sensitive information of the patients of the healthcare industry.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] In his academic article, "Privacy-Enhanced and Multifunctional Health Data Aggregation under Differential Privacy Guarantees," Hao Ren and his team proposes a privacy enhanced and multifunctional health data aggregation scheme (PMHA-DP) under differential privacy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] This aggregation function is designed to protect the aggregated data from cloud servers.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The performance and evaluation done in their study shows that the proposal leads to less communication overhead than the existing data aggregation models currently in place.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] A growing number of vehicles contain internet connection for the convenience of the users.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] This poses yet another threat to the user's privacy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The Internet of vehicles (IoV) is expected to enable intelligent traffic management, intelligent dynamic information services, intelligent vehicle control, etc.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] However, vehicles' data privacy is argued to be a major barrier toward the application and development of IoV, thus causing a wide range of attention.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Local differential privacy (LDP) is the relaxed version of the privacy standard, differential privacy, and it can protect users' data privacy against the untrusted third party in the worst adversarial setting.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The computational costs of using LDP is one concern among researchers as it is quite expensive to implement for such a specific model given that the model needs high mobility and short connection times.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Furthermore, as the number of vehicles increases, the frequent communication between vehicles and the cloud server incurs unexpected amounts of communication cost.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] To avoid the privacy threat and reduce the communication cost, researchers propose to integrate federated learning and local differential privacy (LDP) to facilitate the crowdsourcing applications to achieve the machine learning model.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Since spam phone calls are a growing nuisance in the digital world, researchers have been looking at potential solutions in minimizing this issue.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Federal agencies such as the US Federal Trade Commission (FTC) have been working with telephone carriers to design systems for blocking robocalls.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Furthermore, a number of commercial and smartphone apps that promise to block spam phone calls have been created, but they come with a subtle cost.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] The user's privacy information that comes with giving the app the access to block spam calls may be leaked without the user's consent or knowledge of it even occurring.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Aiming to solve the problem of low data utilization and privacy protection, a personalized differential privacy protection method based on cross-correlation constraints is proposed by researcher Hu.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] By protecting sensitive location points on the trajectory and the sensitive points, this extended differential privacy protection model combines the sensitivity of the user's trajectory location and user privacy protection requirements and privacy budget.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Using autocorrelation Laplace transform, specific white noise is transformed into noise that is related to the user's real trajectory sequence in both time and space.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] This noise data is used to find the cross-correlation constraint mechanics of the trajectory sequence in the model.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] By proposing this model, the researcher Hu's personalized differential privacy protection method is broken down and addresses the issue of adding independent and uncorrelated noise and the same degree of scrambling results in low privacy protection and poor data availability.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Let ε be a positive real number and ${\mathcal {A}}$ be a randomized algorithm that takes a user's private data as input.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Let ${\textrm {im}}{\mathcal {A}}$ denote the image of ${\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] where the probability is taken over the random measure implicit in the algorithm.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/local-differential-privacy] Other formal definitions of local differential privacy concern algorithms that categorize all users' data as input and output a collection of all responses (such as the definition in Raef Bassily, Kobbi Nissim, Uri Stemmer and Abhradeep Guha Thakurta's 2017 paper).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] The objective of PETs is to protect personal data and assure technology users of two key privacy points: their own information is kept confidential, and management of data protection is a priority to the organizations who hold responsibility for any PII.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] PETs allow users to take one or more of the following actions related to personal data that is sent to and used by online service providers, merchants or other users (this control is known as self-determination).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] PETs aim to minimize personal data collected and used by service providers and merchants, use pseudonyms or anonymous data credentials to provide anonymity, and strive to achieve informed consent about giving personal data to online service providers and merchants.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Within private negotiations, the transaction partners may additionally bundle the personal information collection and processing schemes with monetary or non-monetary rewards.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] PETs also provide the opportunity for consumers or people who want privacy-protection to hide their personal identities.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] The process involves masking one's personal information and replacing that information with pseudo-data or an anonymous identity.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Privacy-enhancing technologies can be distinguished based on their assumptions.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Soft privacy technologies are used where it can be assumed that a third-party can be trusted for the processing of data.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] This model is based on compliance, consent, control and auditing.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Example technologies are access control, differential privacy, and tunnel encryption (SSL/TLS).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] An example of soft privacy technologies is increased transparency and access.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Transparency involves granting people with sufficient details about the rationale used in automated decision-making processes.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Additionally, the effort to grant users access is considered soft privacy technology.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Individuals are usually unaware of their right of access or they face difficulties in access, such as a lack of a clear automated process.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] With hard privacy technologies, no single entity can violate the privacy of the user.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] The assumption here is that third-parties cannot be trusted.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Data protection goals include data minimization and the reduction of trust in third-parties.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Examples of such technologies include onion routing, the secret ballot, and VPNs used for democratic elections.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] PETs have evolved since their first appearance in the 1980s.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] PETs for Privacy-Preserving Data Processing are PETs that facilitate data processing or the production of statistics while preserving privacy of the individuals providing raw data, or of the specific raw data elements.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] PETs for Privacy Preserving Data Analytics are a subset of the PETs used for data processing that are specifically designed for the publishing of statistical data.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Examples of privacy-enhancing technologies that are being researched or developed include limited disclosure technology, anonymous credentials, negotiation and enforcement of data handling conditions, and data transaction logs.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Limited disclosure technology provides a way of protecting individuals' privacy by allowing them to share only enough personal information with service providers to complete an interaction or transaction.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] This technology is also designed to limit tracking and correlation of users' interactions with these third parties.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Limited disclosure uses cryptographic techniques and allows users to retrieve data that is vetted by a provider, to transmit that data to a relying party, and have these relying parties trust the authenticity and integrity of the data.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Anonymous credentials are asserted properties or rights of the credential holder that do not reveal the true identity of the holder; the only information revealed is what the holder of the credential is willing to disclose.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] The assertion can be issued by the user, by the provider of the online service or by a third party (another service provider, a government agency, etc.).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Online car rental agencies does not need to know the true identity of the customer.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] It only needs to make sure that the customer is over 23 (as an example), that the customer has a drivers license, health insurance (i.e. for accidents, etc.), and that the customer is paying.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Thus there is no real need to know the customers name nor their address or any other personal information.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Anonymous credentials allow both parties to be comfortable: they allow the customer to only reveal so much data which the car rental agency needs for providing its service (data minimization), and they allow the car rental agency to verify their requirements and get their money.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Negotiation and enforcement of data handling conditions.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Before ordering a product or service online, the user and the online service provider or merchant negotiate the type of personal data that is to be transferred to the service provider.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] This includes the conditions that shall apply to the handling of the personal data, such as whether or not it may be sent to third parties (profile selling) and under what conditions (e.g. only while informing the user), or at what time in the future it shall be deleted (if at all).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] After the transfer of personal data took place, the agreed upon data handling conditions are technically enforced by the infrastructure of the service provider, which is capable of managing and processing and data handling obligations.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Moreover, this enforcement can be remotely audited by the user, for example by verifying chains of certification based on trusted computing modules or by verifying privacy seals/labels that were issued by third party auditing organizations (e.g. data protection agencies).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Thus instead of the user having to rely on the mere promises of service providers not to abuse personal data, users will be more confident about the service provider adhering to the negotiated data handling conditions.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] Lastly, the data transaction log allows users the ability to log the personal data they send to service provider(s), the time in which they do it, and under what conditions.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] These logs are stored and allow users to determine what data they have sent to whom, or they can establish the type of data that is in possession by a specific service provider.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/privacy-enhancing-technologies] This leads to more transparency, which is a pre-requisite of being in control.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] For example, social scientists have used it to ask people whether they use drugs, whether they have illegally installed telephones, or whether they have evaded paying taxes.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] Before abortions were legal, social scientists used the method to ask women whether they had had abortions.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] The concept is somewhat similar to plausible deniability.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] Plausible deniability allows the subject to credibly say that they did not make a statement, while the randomized response technique allows the subject to credibly say that they had not been truthful when making a statement.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] A person is asked if they had sex with a prostitute this month.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] They are then instructed to answer "yes" if the coin comes up tails, and truthfully, if it comes up heads.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] Only they know whether their answer reflects the toss of the coin or their true experience.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] It is very important to assume that people who get heads will answer truthfully, otherwise the surveyor is not able to speculate.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] Half the people—or half the questionnaire population—get tails and the other half get heads when they flip the coin.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] Therefore, half of those people will answer "yes" regardless of whether they have done it.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] The other half will answer truthfully according to their experience.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] So whatever proportion of the group said "no", the true number who did not have sex with a prostitute is double that, based on the assumption that the two halves are probably close to the same as it is a large randomized sampling.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] For example, if 20% of the population surveyed said "no", then the true fraction that did not have sex with a prostitute is 40%.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] The same question can be asked with three cards which are unmarked on one side, and bear a question on the other side.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] The cards are randomly mixed, and laid in front of the subject.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] The subject takes one card, turns it over, and answers the question on it truthfully with either "yes" or "no".
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] The researcher does not know which question has been asked.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] Under the assumption that the "yes" and "no" answers to the control questions cancel each other out, the number of subjects who have had sex with a prostitute is triple that of all "yes" answers in excess of the "no" answers.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] Warner's original version (1965) is slightly different: The sensitive question is worded in two dichotomous alternatives, and chance decides, unknown to the interviewer, which one is to be answered honestly.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] The interviewer gets a "yes" or "no" without knowing to which of the two questions.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] For mathematical reasons chance cannot be "fair" (⁠1/2⁠ and ⁠1/2⁠).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] The interviewed are asked to secretly throw a die and answer the first question only if they throw a 6, otherwise the second question ( $p={\tfrac {1}{6}}$ ).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] The "yes"-answers are now composed of consumers who have thrown a 6 and non-consumers who have thrown a different number.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] Let the result be 75 "yes"-answers out of 100 interviewed ( $YA={\tfrac {3}{4}}$ ).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/randomized-response] If all interviewed have answered honestly then their true proportion of consumers is 1/8 (= 12.5%).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] SDC usually refers to 'output SDC'; ensuring that, for example, a published table or graph does not disclose confidential information about respondents.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] SDC can also describe protection methods applied to the data: for example, removing names and addresses, limiting extreme values, or swapping problematic observations.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] This is sometimes referred to as 'input SDC', but is more commonly called anonymization, de-identification, or microdata protection.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] *Statistical Disclosure Control*) typically cover input SDC and tabular data protection (but not other parts of output SDC).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] This is because these two problems are of direct interest to statistical agencies who supported the development of the field.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] For analytical environments, output rules developed for statistical agencies were generally used until data managers began arguing for specific output SDC for research.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Many kinds of social, economic and health research use potentially sensitive data as a basis for their research, such as survey or Census data, tax records, health records, educational information, etc.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Such information is usually given in confidence, and, in the case of administrative data, not always for the purpose of research.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Researchers are not usually interested in information about one single person or business; they are looking for trends among larger groups of people.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] However, the data they use is, in the first place, linked to individual people and businesses, and SDC ensures that these cannot be identified from published data, no matter how detailed or broad.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] It is possible that at the end of data analysis, the researcher somehow singles out one person or business through their research.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] For example, a researcher may identify the exceptionally good or bad service in a geriatric department within a hospital in a remote area, where only one hospital provides such care.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] In that case, the data analysis 'discloses' the identity of the hospital, even if the dataset used for analysis was properly anonymised or de-identified.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Statistical disclosure control will identify this disclosure risk and ensure the results of the analysis are altered to protect confidentiality.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] It requires a balance between protecting confidentiality and ensuring the results of the data analysis are still useful for statistical research.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Output SDC relies upon having a set of rules that can be followed by an output checker; for example, that a frequency table must have a minimum number of observations, or that survival tables should be right-censored for extreme values.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] The value and drawbacks of rules for frequency and magnitude tables have been discussed extensively since the late 20th Century.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] However, with awareness of the increasing need for rules for other types of analyses, a more structured approach is needed.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Some statistical outputs, such as frequency tables, have a high level of inherent risk: differencing, low numbers, class disclosure.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] They therefore need to be checked before release, ideally by someone with some understanding of the data, to ensure that there is no meaningful risk on release.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] These are referred to as 'unsafe statistics'.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] However, there are some statistics, such as the coefficients from modelling, that have no meaningful risk and therefore can be released with no further checks.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] By separating statistics into 'safe' and 'unsafe', output checks can be concentrated on the latter, improving both security and efficiency.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] This is less important for official statistics, where 'unsafe' statistics such as counts, means, medians and simple indexes dominate the outputs.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] However, for research output this is important, as a great deal of research output (particularly estimates and test statistics) is inherently 'safe'.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] The safe/unsafe model is useful but limited with two simple categories; within those categories, guidelines for SDC largely consist of long lists of statistics and how to handle them.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] In 2023, the SACRO project https://dareuk.org.uk/driver-project-sacro/ undertook to review the whole field and see whether a more useful classification scheme could be introduced.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] The result is the 'statistical barn' (or 'statbarn') concept.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] They also cover most graph forms, where the graph can be converted into the appropriate statsbarn (for example, a pie chart is another form of frequency table).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] The SACRO manual provides guidance on what to look out for, and the rules to be followed for checking.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] A lookup table between statstistcs/graphs and statbarns is available on outputchecking.org.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] There are two main approaches to output SDC: *principles-based* and *rules-based.* In principles-based systems, disclosure control attempts to uphold a specific set of fundamental principles—for example, "no person should be identifiable in released microdata".
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Rules-based systems, in contrast, are evidenced by a specific set of rules that a person performing disclosure control follows (for example, "any frequency must be based on at least five observations"), after which the data are presumed to be safe to release.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] In general, official statistics are rules-based; research environments are more likely to be principles-based.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] In research environments, the choice of output-checking regime can have significant operational implications.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] In rules-based SDC, a rigid set of rules is used to determine whether or not the results of data analysis can be released.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] The rules are applied consistently, which makes it obvious what kinds of output are acceptable.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Rules-based systems are good for ensuring consistency across time, across data sources, and across production teams, which makes them appealing for statistical agencies.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Rules-based systems also work well for remote job serves such as microdata.no or Lissy.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] However, because the rules are inflexible, either disclosive information may still slip through, or the rules are over-restrictive and may only allow for results that are too broad for useful analysis to be published.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] In practice, research environments running rules-based systems may have to bring flexibility in 'ad hoc' systems.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] The Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) uses a rules-based approach to releasing statistics and research results.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] In principles-based SDC, both the researcher and the output checker are trained in SDC.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] They receive a set of rules, which are rules-of-thumb rather than hard rules as in rules-based SDC.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] This means that in principle, any output may be approved or refused.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] The rules-of-thumb are a starting point for the researcher.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] A researcher may request outputs which breach the 'rules of thumb' as long as (1) they are non-disclosive (2) they are important and (3) this is an exceptional request.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] It is up to the researcher to prove that any 'unsafe' outputs are non-disclosive, but the checker has the final say.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Since there are no hard rules, this requires knowledge on disclosure risks and judgment from both the researcher and the checker.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] It requires training and an understanding of statistics and data analysis, although it has been argued that this can be used to make the process more efficient than a rules-based model.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] In the UK all major secure research environments in social science and public health, with the exception of Northern Ireland, are principles-based.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] This includes the UK Data Service's Secure Data Service, the Office for National Statistics' Secure Research Service, the Scottish Safe Havens, Secure Anonymized Information Linkage (SAIL) and OpenSAFELY.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Many contemporary statistical disclosure control techniques, such as generalization and cell suppression, have been shown to be vulnerable to attack by a hypothetical data intruder.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] For example, Cox showed in 2009 that Complementary cell suppression typically leads to "over-protected" solutions because of the need to suppress both primary and complementary cells, and even then can lead to the compromise of sensitive data when exact intervals are reported.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Many of the rules are arbitrary and reflect data owner's unwillingness to be different, rather than solid evidence.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] For example, Ritchie demonstrated the choice of a minimum threshold is more about an organisation's wish to be in line with others than any statistical rationale.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] A more substantive criticism is that the theoretical models used to explore control measures are not appropriate for guides for practical action.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Hafner et al. provide a practical example of how a change in perspective can generate substantially different results.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Artificial intelligence and machine learning models present different risks for output checking.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] The GRAIMATTER project https://dareuk.org.uk/sprint-exemplar-project-graimatter/ provided some initial guidance and automatic tools.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] These were extended and simplified as part of the SACRO project (see below), and more guidelines for data services staff added.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] The SDC-REBOOT community network https://www.jiscmail.ac.uk/cgi-bin/webadmin?A0=SDC-REBOOT is currently co-ordinating the ongoing development of the tools and guidance.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Output checking is generally labour-intensive, as it requires analysts who can understand what they are looking at and make a judgement about whether to release an output.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] There is therefore considerable interest in automated checking.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] tau-Argus and sdcTable are fully-automated open-source EoPR tools for tabular data protection (frequency and magnitude tables).
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] They are designed to work with multiple tables.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Metadata needs to be set up describing the output(s), and the control parameters.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] They provide the output checkers with extensive information on potential problems, including secondary disclosure across tables.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] They can also carry out correction measures, from suppression and simple rounding to secondary suppression and controlled tabular rounding.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] They do not deal with non-tabular outputs.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] Because of the need to rewrite the metadata for each table, these tools are poorly suited for research use.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] However, in official statistics, where the same tables are being repeatedly generated and where secondary differencing is considered a significant problem, the investment in setting up the tools can be very cost-effective.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] SACRO (Semi-autonomous checking of research outputs) is a WPR tool, originally commissioned (ACRO) by Eurostat in 2020 as a proof-of-concept to show that a general-purpose output checking tool could be developed.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] In 2023 the UK Medical Research Council commissioned a generalised version (SACRO) which would work with multiple languages (as of 2024: Stata, R and Python) and provide a more user-friendly interface.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] SACRO directly implements the statbarns model and is principles-based; hence, it is 'semi-automatic' as it allows users to request exceptions and for output checkers to override the automated recommendations.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] All UK social science secure facilities, and most UK public health secure facilities, are planning to adopt it.
[src:differential-privacy-applied/statistical-disclosure-control] The software is available on GitHub at https://github.com/AI-SDC, which also contains links to the original ACRO and tools for assessing AI models.
